This document describle the implementation of smart card authentication on RHEL 8/9 at Enterpise Level with a focus on DoD.

Smart card authentication replaces passwords with physical tokens containing private keys. Users insert the card and enter a PIN to achieve two-factor security. Administrators use specific tools to manage card content and configure Identity Management servers (IPA or AD) and clients to support these workflows.
Requirements:
- AD or IPA
- workstation or server
- supported Card reader
- RootCAs (entire CA chain) in PEM format
- A user CAC certificate for testing
- workstation/server must be joined to AD or IPA.
- packages:
  - krb5-pkinit
  - opensc
  - pcsc-lite
  - pcsc-tools

================= Active Directory Authentication Provider ===================

1. Install required RPM packages and theirs depencies
# dnf install -y krb5-pkinit opensc pcsc-lite pcsc-tool

2. Add RootCA and any Local Domain Controller Certs to the system trust store. 
# cat DC-01.pem >> RootCA.pem
# cat DC-02.pem >> RootCA.pem
# cp RootCA.pem DC.pem /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors

3. Create a certificate bundle of the RootCA and local DC and add the CA bundle to the System Security Services Daemon (SSSD) trust store.
# cat RootCA.pem DC.pem > /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem
# cat local_DC_(s)_Crt.pem >> /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem   ## NOte: this step could be ignored if all DCs certs were added to the RootCA.pem file.

4. Extract a user CAC certificate from Windows ActivClient console or Certmgr

***** WINDOWS ********
certmgr > Personal > Cerficates > select cert with smart card logon intended purposes > copy to file (saved as user_cert.dem)


***** LINUX **********
Insert CAC in reader them use PKCS11-tool list certs obects
# pkcs11-tool -O --type cert
copy cert to a file in DER format
# pkcs11-tool --read-object --id 01 --type cert --output-file user_cert.der
convert user cert into PEM
# openssl x509 -inform DER -in user_cert.der -outform PEM > user_cert.pem

5. Transfer user's CAC certification from window to location on Linux or distributed file system.
#sftp user_name@workstation
> put user_cert.dem

6. Convert the user'c CAC certificate from DEM to PEM form
# openssl x509 -inform dem -in user_cert.dem -out user_cert.pem

7. Use sssctl utility do see user CAC certificate details attributes. The certificates attribute will be used for matching and mapping rules to correctly map The certificate to AD users.

# ldapsearch -x -H ldap://DOMAIN_MANE -D "CN=, OU=,OU=,OU=,OU=,DC=,DC=" -W -b "OU=,OU=,OU=,DC=,DC=" "User_NAME"  # LDAP query

# CERT=$(openssl x509 -in user_cert.pem.pem -outform der | base64 -w0)  ## based 64 encoded cert
# sssctl cert-show $CERT
# sssctl cert-eval-rule $CERT --match="<EKU>msScLogin,clientAuth,pkinit" --map="(userPrincipalName={subject_nt_principal})"  ## cert matching and mapping rule testing


8. Configure the workstation or the client kerberos to trust the Root CAs and Local Domain controler certs by addind the certs to the system trusted store.
# vim /etc/krb5.conf.d/smart-card-auth.conf
[libdefaults]
pkinit_anchors = FILE:/etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/RootCA.pem DC.pem

[realms]
DOMAIN_NAME = {
  pkinit_anchors = FILE:/etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem
  pkinit_kdc_hostname = DC-01.DOMAIN_NAME
  pkinit_kdc_hostname = DC-02.DOMAIN_NAME
}

9. Add the lines below in a drop in file in SSSD auxilliary directory for smarth card authentication
# vim /etc/sssd/conf.d/smart-card-auth.conf
[domain/DOMAIN_NAME]
krb5_auth_timeout = 300
auth_provider = ad

[pam]
pam_cert_auth = True
p11_child_timeout = 300


[certmap/DOMAIN_NAME/smartcard_rule]
debug_level = 9
#matchrule = "<ISSUER>CN=DOD ID CA-.*"
#matchrule = <EKU>msScLogin,clientAuth,pkinit
matchrule = <ISSUER>CN=DOD ID CA-.*<EKU>msScLogin,clientAuth,pkinit              ## catch all CA rule
maprule = (userPrincipalName={subject_principal})
domains = DOMAIN_NAME

10. Start/restart/enable services 
# sssctl config-check
# systemctl --now enable sssd.service pcscd.service

11. Enable system wide smart card authentication
authselect select sssd with-smartcard --force

12. Use sssctl and opessl utility for sanity check
# openssl verify -CAfile /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem user)cert.pem
# sssctl user-checks -s gdm-smartcard andre.fankam -a auth
